I think using PUT /lead/:leadID/status is a good api design.

As for the if-else, you could use a switch statement to make it a bit cleaner, but if you would like to create a generic solution, then I would recommend keeping a map of the status id to the required fields to copy for each status eg
```
const statuses : { [key:number]:{ field: string, values: []string; } = {
    14: {field: &quot;termine&quot;, values: [&quot;date&quot;]}
    ....other states
};
```

This will allow you to generify the handling of status updates like this:
```
const statusCfg = statuses[req.body.status];
for (const valFld of statusCfg.values) {
    lead[statusCfg.field][valFld] = resp.body[valFld];
}
```

Ultimately this is down to how different the handling of each status is, if it cannot be generified in this way you may want to look at having seperate handlers for each status that adhere to a single interface. You could then still use a map to lookup the correct handler.

